  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Projet DJAM</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Intercommunity dialogue is enhanced by the development of small agro-pastoral territorial projects
Pastor / farmer conflicts in areas identified as at risk of violent extremism are mitigated through inter-community dialogue and social agreements.
Access to pastoral resources and their development through the development of sustainable economic opportunities in the pastoral and agro-pastoral fields for the benefit of vulnerable groups (young people, women) reduces their vulnerability to radicalization
Les m&#xE9;canismes de dialogue et de r&#xE9;solution des conflits sont capitalis&#xE9;s, valoris&#xE9;s, diss&#xE9;min&#xE9;s et mis en application dans les zones nouvelles de tension</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">To support municipalities, local authorities and pastoral organizations in the operationalization of rural land systems and structures.
To contribute to the finalization in a concerted manner with the actors (Regional Council, DGAT) of the land development plan (SAF) in the Sahel regions
To promote nonviolent conflict management through fora, animated discussions of caravans of peace, radio broadcasts.
To promote youth pools and women for peace in 60 villages.
To support the development of common pastoral and water resources management rules through informal arrangements
To support the municipalities to set up and operationalize systems of non-violent management of community tensions and agro-pastoral conflicts
To Secure pastoral areas by demarcating and marking 200 km of passage corridors
To restore / develop pastoral and agropastoral areas
To strengthen the Pastoral Alert Service (SAP), developed by VSF-B, using ICT and based on voicemail.
To identify and delimit (geographical area, mapping of actors, outlets) economic development poles around livestock-meat and milk sectors.
To develop competitive economic models (fodder production, cattle fattening, dairy processing) promoted by young people and women</narrative>
  </description>
